INSTALLATION INSTRUCTIONS
-------------------------


	Windows:

	As of version 1.0.1 of the Cog Development Application,
a Windows binary executable (win32) is available. This program is
currently available as a zip file, although an automated installer
is under development. Simply unzip the zip file (being certain
to maintain the archived directory structure) and double-click
the "CogDevApp.exe" file to run the program.

	You will still need to instal Java and Jython in order to convert
game files developed with the Development Application into a
format which can be read by the Java Applet version of the Cog Engine.
A new version of the Cog Engine is currently under development, which
features the ability to run games on the local machine with any
additional software.

	See the Execute-From-Source Installation Tips below for more
information.


	Linux:

	A binary version of the Cog Development Application is not
yet available under linux, although work is currently underway to
produce one. However, if you have installed the necessary prerequisites
on your system, you shouldn't have much trouble executing the source
with a command such as "python CogDevApp.py" from the command line.

	See the Execute-From-Source Installation Tips below for more
information.


Development Prerequisites
------------------------

Python information is available at:
http://www.python.org/

Python/GTK information is available at:
http://www.daa.com.au/~james/pygtk/
http://theopenlab.uml.edu/pygtools/

Jython information is available at:
http://jython.sourceforge.net/

(You also need the Python/Gnome Libraries, and the Glade Libraries)

Python/Gnome information is available at:
http://www.daa.com.au/~james/gnome/

Glade information is available at:
http://glade.gnome.org/


If you are using RedHat Linux, the following rpms (and their own
prerequisits) should be installed:
python
pygtk
pygnome
pygtk-libglade
pygnome-libglade

	All of these packages are included on the RedHat install cds,
as of version 7.2. If I have missed any packages, please email me.

If you are using Debian Linux, the following debs (and their own
prerequisits) should be installed:
python-base
python-gtk
python-gnome
python-glade
libglade
libglade-gnome

	Again, all of these packages are available as part of the base
install, as of version 2.2 (potato).


Execute-From-Source Installation Tips
-------------------------------------

For Linux:

1) Download and install the above listed prerequisits.

2) Uncompress and extract the source files.

3) Edit the import_cog_data.py and export_cog_data.py scripts such that
the "cPython_library_path" variable points to your local installation of
python.

4) You can execute the CogDevApp GUI program by typing ./CogDevApp.py in
the resulting directory.

5) You can convert game modules create with the CogDevApp into files
readable by the Cog Engine via the "export_cog_data.py" script, and you
convert those file back for editing using the "import_cog_data.py" script.

6) The current version of the CogDevApp includes class files from version
1.0 of the CogEngine (the current version). If you are going to be using
CogDevApp with a different version of the CogEngine, you will need to
replace these class files with the new ones.


Example (Under Linux):
tar xvzf CogDevApp-1.0.1-source.tar.gz
tar xvzf CyconOdyssey-0.96-data.tar.gz
cp CyconOdyssey-0.96/Cycon-COG.dat CogDevApp-1.0.1
cd CogDevApp-1.0.1
./import_cog_data.py Cycon-COG.dat Cycon-COG.dev
./CogDevApp.py Cycon-COG.dev
./export_cog_data.py Cycon-COG.dev Cycon-COG.dat


For Windows:

1) Down the installation program for Python from python.org.
The current supported version is 2.1.

2) Run the installation program, and take note of the installtion
directory you choose. (The default installation directory is
"C:\Python21". We shall assume this to be the directory you choose to
install into for the remainder of this document.)

3) Download the current CogDevApp source zip file, if you haven't done so
already, and unzip the files into a new folder. If you don't already have
a zip file utility, you can find one at winzip.com.

4) Open the folder you installed the CogDevApp files into, and
double-click the "CogDevApp.py" file. If python is associated
with the file correctly, you should be finished. Otherwise, continue onto
step 5.

5) Open a command line window, either from the program files menu, or by
entering the appropriate command into the run dialog box (cmd for windows
nt, command for windows 9x/ME).

6) Load the CogDevApp.py according to this example:
cd CogDevApp-1.0.1
C:\python21\python CogDevApp.py

7) Enjoy!


Converting From CogDevApp files to CogEngine files:

	Currently you'll need to install a JVM and Jython
(jython.sourceforge.net) to do this. A program is under development to
remove this requirement however. If you want to try to install Jython
yourself, you can use the import_cog_data.py and export_cog_data.py files
to convert between the two formats.




